<p>
    In the previous pods of this unit,
    we looked at molecules from a simple point of view:
    hot is faster, slow is cooler.
    In this pod, we will learn the rigorous definitions
    needed to begin creating a more precise model of molecular motion.
</p>


<p class="definition" data-word = "Kinetic Theory of Matter">
    The <strong>Kinetic Theory of Matter</strong> is a physical theory
    that all matter is composed of pieces that are always in motion.
    (The word <emph>kinetic</emph> means <emph>in motion</emph>).
</p>

<p class="definition" data-word = 'Temperature'>
    Temperature is the average molecular kinetic energy of a substance.
    In other words, it is a measure of how much kinetic energy the molecules
    of a substance possess.
    All objects with the same temperature (in thermal equilibrium) have the
    same average molecular kinetic energy <emph>regardless</emph> of the state of matter.
</p>

<p class="definition" data-word = "Absolute Zero">
    <strong>Absolute Zero</strong> is the temperature at which all particles
    stop moving. Thus, their kinetic energy and tempearture are zero.
    <br>
    Absolute zero has never been achieved, and most scientists think
    it is impossible to achieve. It is only a theoretical idea.
</p>

