<h4>
    Random motion of molecules vs. translational motion
</h4>

<p>
    Assuming you are working on this while working on a table,
    take a look at the table.
    Is the table moving?
    I hope it is not!
    But, it is made of atoms that are bound together into large molecules,
    and these atoms are molecules are moving!
</p>

<p>
    Let's imagine that somebody picks up the table and moves it somewhere else.
    Are the atoms in the table moving? YES!
    However, they are all moving in the same direction, together.
    This represents the <strong>translational motion</strong> of matter.
    In addition, the atoms are also virbating in place, but they do not move
    together, so we cannot directly observe this motion.
    This represents the <strong>random motion</strong> of molecules.
</p>

<p>
    THe kinetic theory of matter applies only to the <strong>random motion</strong>
    of molecules.
    The definition of temperature is "The average kinetic energy of the random motion of molecules
    in an object."
</p>

<h4>
    Measuring Thermal Energy
</h4>

<p>
    Temperature is a measure of energy, but we can't measure it in the same way we
    can measure all of the other forms of energy!
    Most forms of energy, such as kinetic energy or elastic potential energy,
    we measure as a certain number of Joules.
    But, we could never figure out how to add up the kinetic energy of every
    single molecule and atom in some substace in order to find out how many
    Joules of thermal energy it has!
    So, thermal energy cannot be measured in the same way.
</p>

<p>
    However, we can measure thermal energy using the concept of temperature.
    We know that an objects temperature is a measure of the average
    kinetic energy of the random motion of the molecules.
    We also know that if two objects that do not have the same temperature
    are in thermal contact, heat will move between them until they do have
    the same temperature. That state is called <emph>thermal equilbrium</emph>
    and is explored extensviely in
    <a href = '/unit/thermodynamics/heat_transfer_temperature_mathematical'>another unit</a>.
</p>



<h4>
    Why Temperature is a Scale
</h4>

<p>
    Something makes temperature very different than every other quantity we learn about in this class:
    it is defined on a scale, not an absolute.
</p>

<p>
    Look at the following examples:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Velocity is a measure of how fast something is moving.
        If velocity is zero, something is not moving.
    </li>
    <li>
        Force is a measure of how something is pushed or pulled.
        If force is zero, it isn't being pushed or pulled at all.
    </li>
    <li>
        Electric current is a measure of how many electrons flow through a point.
        If current is zero, no electrons flow through that point.
    </li>
    <li>
        Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of the random motion
        of the molecules.
        And if the temperature is 0&#176;C, the average kinetic enerfy og the random motion
        of molecules is.....NOT zero!
    </li>
</ul>

<p>
    Why is temperature different from velocity, force, and electric current?
    Velocity, force, and electric current are <emph>quantities</emph>,
    whereas temperature in Celsius is not a quantity, it is a <emph>scale</emph>.
    The inventors of thermal physics only knew how to measure temperature by comparing
    the temperatures of different items. They had no concept that temperature represented
    a quantity which could be zero!
    Therefore, they invented a "scale" in which the
    point 0 does not actually reflect zero.
</p>


<p>
    However, there <emph>is</emph> a way that temperature can be expressed as a quantity not a scale:
    if you use the Kelvin.
    If the temperature is zero Kelvin, the molecules are in fact, not moving!
    This makes Kelvin a true quantity, like velocity, force, and electric current.
    Therefore, when Kelvin, you <emph>do not</emph> say "degrees Kelvin"
    you only say "Kelvin." And, you never write the little circle "&#176;K", you just write "K".
</p>


<p>
    In practice, the Celsius scale is used far more than Kelvin, even though it is not
    That is because most items you find on a typical day are between -20&#176;C and 40&#176;C.
    Furthermore, water freezes at 0&#176;C and boils at 100&#176;C.
    It is much easier to use these numbers than express everything in hundreds of Kelvin!
</p>

